&lt;div class="post-text" itemprop="text"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Using Opera 11.51 here, it doesn't actually like the fact that you use &lt;code&gt;onsubmit()&lt;/code&gt; as a function name. Presumably because &lt;code&gt;onsubmit()&lt;/code&gt; is actually already an eventhandler hook of a &lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;button&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt; element itself. I presume other browsers won't like this function name either.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So, first off, rename the function. Let's assume &lt;code&gt;dosubmit()&lt;/code&gt; here.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Furthermore, you should wrap a button in a &lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;form&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt; element. And because a default button, acts as a submit button, the form is being submitted, causing the page to reload.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To prevent this, you should let the function &lt;code&gt;return false;&lt;/code&gt; and call the function like so &lt;code&gt;onclick="return dosubmit()"&lt;/code&gt;, if you are going to call it inline like this, or make the button a button of type &lt;code&gt;button&lt;/code&gt;, like so: &lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;button type="button" onclick="dosubmit()"&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

