&lt;div class="post-text" itemprop="text"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You will have to make some kind of PHP change, otherwise your JS has no way of knowing who the current user is.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you just mean you don't want to mix PHP in the middle of your Javascript code, you could have some one-off PHP at the top of the document that sets up any globals:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;script&amp;gt;
var myAppGlobals = {};

myAppGlobals.showCandyMenu = &amp;lt;?php echo ($user-&amp;gt;name === 'Ben' ? 'true': 'false'); ?&amp;gt;;
// or
myAppGlobals.userName = '&amp;lt;?php echo addslashes($user-&amp;gt;name); ?&amp;gt;';
&amp;lt;/script&amp;gt;
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;and then use&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;if (myAppGlobals.showCandyMenu)
    $("#CandyMenu").show();

// or

if (myAppGlobals.userName === 'Ben')
    $("#CandyMenu").show();
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;from your Javascript later on. You're still mixing PHP and JS, but at least you're doing it all up the top instead of mixed in all over the place.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Of course, bear in mind that any method you use to set the visibility of a menu from the client side is open to abuse – anyone with JS knowledge would be able to delve in and display that menu option. Whether that's a problem or not is up to you.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

