* and the function's return value will be assigned to $a variable
* now $a will contain value 'hello world';
*/
$a = foo();
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;if you try printing the variable &lt;code&gt;$a&lt;/code&gt; it will simply print the value it contains and not call the function once again, since &lt;code&gt;$a&lt;/code&gt; now contains 'hello world';&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;by echoing $a variable multiple times.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;echo $a;
echo $a;
echo $a;
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;will simply print the value &lt;code&gt;hello world&lt;/code&gt; three times and not call the function three times.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;but when you call the function multiple times for example.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;$a = foo();
